\details{
\subsection{Subclassing}{

Subclasses should call \code{super$initialize(name, description)} and then
register their arguments with \verb{$new_argument()}. After all arguments are
registered, set \verb{$template} to control how arguments are assembled into
the final command string. A typical pattern:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{super$initialize(name = "mycommand", description = "Does something")

self$new_argument(
  label          = "param_a",
  description    = "First parameter",
  command_format = "a \{value\}",
  default_value  = 5
)

all_labels <- sapply(private$.arguments, `[[`, "label")
self$template <- paste("\{", all_labels, "\}", sep = "")
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Argument system}{

Each argument registered via \verb{$new_argument()} is stored as a
\link{CommandArgument} object. Arguments support:
\itemize{
\item \strong{\code{command_format}} — a \link[glue:glue]{glue} string (e.g.,
\code{"replic {value}"}) or a function returning the formatted TNT
command fragment.
\item \strong{\code{pretty_format}} — an optional glue string or function used by
\verb{$format()} for human-readable display.
\item \strong{\code{default_value}} — the initial value assigned when no user value
is supplied.
}

Subclasses typically expose each argument as an active binding that
delegates to \verb{$get_argument_value()} and \verb{$set_argument_value()},
providing validation on assignment.
}

\subsection{Rendering}{

\verb{$render()} assembles the command string by evaluating each argument
through its \code{command_format} and interpolating the results into
\verb{$template}. If \verb{$template} is a function, it is called with the
current argument values as named parameters. Arguments that fail to
render are silently omitted. The final output has the form
\code{"{name} {arguments};"}.
}
